 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are units in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Here we are describing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a quotient of a polynomial ring, but we can also describe it as a finite
 module extension over a polynomial ring.
 Namely, we can write it as 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Z}[y][\sqrt{g}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=y^{2}-(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)=y^{2}-g,\label{eq:antilocal2-1}
\end{equation}

