end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The thick black curve is 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})=\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(f)$
\end_inset

 whereas the thick red curve is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(u)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 do not intersect: this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (and hence a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}A$
\end_inset

).
 The point is that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\mathfrak{p}):=u\text{ mod }\mathfrak{p}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in X$
\end_inset

.
 The closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{a,b}=\langle x-a,y-b\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 There's also the generic point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we equip 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 with the Euclidean topology.
 Then we see that it is disconnected since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X(\mathbb{R})=\left(\{u>0\}\cap X(\mathbb{R})\right)\cup\left(\{u<0\}\cap X(\mathbb{R})\right),
\]

\end_inset

however in the Zariski topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is irreducible since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, so certainly 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is connected in the Zariski topology.
 The Jacobian matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{J}_{f} & =\begin{pmatrix}\partial_{x}f\\
\partial_{y}f
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}4x^{3}+30x^{2}-70x+50\\
2y
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, it's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{J}_{f}(a,b):=\mathrm{J}_{f}\,\,\text{mod}\,\mathfrak{m}_{a,b}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all closed points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{a,b}\in X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 Alternatively, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}f=\partial_{x}f\mathrm{d}x+\partial_{y}f\mathrm{d}y=(4x^{3}+30x^{2}-70x+50)\mathrm{d}x+2y\mathrm{d}y.
\]

\end_inset

Thus when we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}f=0$
\end_inset

, then for 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} & =-\frac{4x^{3}+30x^{2}-70x+50}{2y}.\label{eq:slopejklf-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The DeRham complex of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega_{A}:=0\to A\to
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now, we want to see what the curve looks like at in affine neighborhood
 of the point at infinity 
\begin_inset Formula $[0:1:0]$
\end_inset

.
 To do this let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{A}=\mathbb{Z}[x,z]\slash\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{f}=\widetilde{y}^{2}-(\widetilde{x}-\widetilde{y})(\widetilde{x}-2\widetilde{y})(x-3\widetilde{y})(x-4\widetilde{y}),\label{eq:homogenizefds-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{X}=\mathrm{Spec}\,\widetilde{A}$
\end_inset

.
 We can visualize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{X}$
\end_inset

 in the picture below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plotcurveatinfty.jpg

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{X}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}_{\widetilde{a},\widetilde{b}}=\langle\widetilde{x}-\widetilde{a},\widetilde{y}-\widetilde{b}\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{a},\widetilde{b})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}(\widetilde{a},\widetilde{b})=0$
\end_inset

.
 We have a ring isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon\widetilde{A}_{\widetilde{y}}\to A_{y}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}(\widetilde{x})=x/y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}(\widetilde{y})=1/y$
\end_inset

, with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A_{y}\to\widetilde{A}_{\widetilde{y}}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\widetilde{x}/\widetilde{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)=1/\widetilde{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi}(\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}_{\widetilde{a},\widetilde{b}}) & =\varphi(\langle\widetilde{x}-\widetilde{a},\widetilde{y}-\widetilde{b}\rangle)\\
 & =\langle x/y-\widetilde{a},1/y-\widetilde{b}\rangle\\
 & =\langle x-\widetilde{a}y,1-\widetilde{b}y\rangle\\
 & =\langle x-\widetilde{a}y,y-1/\widetilde{b}\rangle\\
 & =\langle x-\widetilde{a}/\widetilde{b},y-1/\widetilde{b}\rangle\\
 & =\langle x-a,y-b\rangle\\
 & =\mathfrak{m}_{a,b},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\widetilde{a}/\widetilde{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=1/\widetilde{b}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\widetilde{\varphi}(\mathfrak{m}_{a,b})=\widetilde{\mathfrak{m}}_{\widetilde{a},\widetilde{b}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}\widetilde{x}=\frac{y\mathrm{d}x-x\mathrm{d}y}{y^{2}}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{d}\widetilde{y}=-\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{y^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A Blowup Algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle y^{2}-x^{3}-x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\langle\overline{x},\overline{y}\rangle$
\end_inset

 (we drop the overlines from 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}$
\end_inset

 in just write 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in onder to simplify notation in what follows), and equip 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-filtration making 
\begin_inset Formula $R=(Q^{n})$
\end_inset

 into a filtered ring.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R[u,v]\to\mathrm{bl}(R)$
\end_inset

 be the unique surjective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u)=xt$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(v)=yt$
\end_inset

.
 The kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R[u,v]$
\end_inset

 which is homogeneous in the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ker\varphi=\langle v^{2}-(x+1)u^{2},xv-yu\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Thus we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{bl}(R)\cong\Bbbk[x,y,u,v]\slash\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{a}=\langle v^{2}-(x+1)u^{2},xv-yu,y^{2}-x^{3}-x^{2}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{bl}(R)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to an algebraic subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{x,y}^{2}\times\mathbb{P}_{u,v}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=R[v]\slash\langle v^{2}-(x+1),xv-y\rangle$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $U=Z\cap(\mathbb{A}^{2}\times\mathrm{D}(u))$
\end_inset

.
 We can localize further by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $B=A_{x}=R[v]\slash\langle v-y/x\rangle$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $V=Z\cap(\mathrm{D}(x)\times\mathrm{D}(u))$
\end_inset

 .
 We have a canonical ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon R\to A$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion map.
 Let us try to understand this homomorphism from a geometric point of view.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}_{\Bbbk}(y^{2}-x^{3}-x^{2})$
\end_inset

 be affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{2}$
\end_inset

 defined by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}=x^{3}+x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

: they are all of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b)}=\langle x-a,y-b\rangle
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in X$
\end_inset

, that is, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}=a^{3}+a^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we can visualize the closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 as below: 
\begin_inset Branch tikzcd
inverted 0
status collapsed

