\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, the prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b),[1:t]}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in X$
\end_inset

 together with the unique line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=tx$
\end_inset

 that passes through that point and the origin, where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 represents the slope of that line.
 There are two points lying over the origin: namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{(0,0),[1:1]}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{(0,0),[1:-1]}$
\end_inset

, corresponding to the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)\in V$
\end_inset

 together with the lines 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-x$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon R\to A$
\end_inset

 induces a continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\iota\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,A\to\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{\mathrm{a}}\iota(\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b),[1,t]})=\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b)}.
\]

\end_inset

This corresponds to the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon U\to X$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(a,b,t)=(a,b).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that in the image above there are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

missing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 points.
 For instance, we drew a vertical dashed line in the image above; it should
 correspond to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, but it has nowhere to go under this projection.
 In fact, this missing line corresponds to the extra point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}(\mathrm{bl}(R))$
\end_inset

 which doesn't belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
hyperellitpic curve 
\series default
is an algebraic curve of genus 
\begin_inset Formula $g>1$
\end_inset

, given by an equation of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}+h(x)y=f(x),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2g+1>4$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2g+2>4$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 distinct roots and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $<g+2$
\end_inset

 (if the characteristic of the ground field is not 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, one can take 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)=0$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A Surface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}=\mathrm{V}_{\Bbbk}(f_{t})\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{3}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{t}=(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}-1)^{2}+(x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}-1)^{2}-t=g_{1}^{2}+g_{2}^{2}-t=\|\boldsymbol{g}\|^{2}-t
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}=(g_{1},g_{2})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}=x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}-1$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0.1$
\end_inset

, we can picture 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0.1}$
\end_inset

 as below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename genus3.jpg
	lyxscale 50
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Jacobian matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{J}_{f_{t}} & =\begin{pmatrix}\partial_{x}f_{t}\\
\partial_{y}f_{t}\\
\partial_{z}f_{t}
\end{pmatrix}=4\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}g_{1}\\
x_{2}(g_{1}+g_{2})\\
x_{3}g_{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{t}=\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{J}_{f_{t}})=\{\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{3}\mid\mathrm{J}_{f_{t}}(\boldsymbol{a})=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{3}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\Delta_{t}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathrm{V}_{\Bbbk}(g_{1},g_{2})$
\end_inset

 (meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(\boldsymbol{a})=g_{2}(\boldsymbol{a})=0$
\end_inset

).
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $t\neq0,2$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 has no singular points since 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}\cap\Delta_{t}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 in this case.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 is a singular point since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}\in S_{2}\cap\Delta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 has lots of singular points.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\pm1,0,\pm1),(\pm1,0,\mp1)\}$
\end_inset

 are all singular points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We can desribe 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 as being the fibre at 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 with respect to the morphism of affine 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon S\to\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk,\tau}^{1}$
\end_inset

 (here we are indicating that the coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk,\tau}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\tau]$
\end_inset

) where 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathrm{Spec}(\Bbbk[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\tau]\slash f_{\tau})$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\Bbbk[\tau]\to\Bbbk[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\tau]\slash f_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 (which is just inclusion map).
 In particular, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk\to\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk,\tau}^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the morphism of affine 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-schemes which corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\tau]\to\Bbbk[\tau]\slash\langle\tau-t\rangle\simeq\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 which sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the pullback of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon S\to\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk,\tau}^{1}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk\to\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk,\tau}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Bbbk[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}]\slash f_{t}\simeq(\Bbbk[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\tau]\slash f_{\tau})\otimes_{\Bbbk}\Bbbk[\tau]\slash\langle\tau-t\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Note that the morphism of affine 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon S\to\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk,\tau}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is flat since the inclusion map of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\Bbbk[\tau]\to\Bbbk[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\tau]\slash f_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is flat.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
An Elliptic Curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study the elliptic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 defind by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}=x^{3}-51$
\end_inset

.
 One calculates its discriminant to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=2^{4}\cdot3^{3}\cdot51^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Degeneration to a Monomial Ideal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\Bbbk[x,y]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R'=\Bbbk[x',y']$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\Bbbk[x,y,x',y']\slash J$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\langle x\rangle\langle x-x',y-y'\rangle=\langle x^{2}-xx',xy-xy'\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

We also set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X'=\mathrm{Spec}\,R'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,S$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have two morphisms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to X'$
\end_inset

 which correspond to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $R\to S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R'\to S$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a,b)\in\Bbbk^{2}$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{p}=\langle x-a,y-b\rangle$
\end_inset

, and similarly for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p'=(a',b')\in\Bbbk^{2}$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{p'}'=\langle x'-a',y'-b'\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{p}$
\end_inset

 denote the fiber of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{p'}'$
\end_inset

 denote the fiber of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{p}\simeq\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{0}$
\end_inset

 whereas
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{p'}'\simeq\begin{cases}
\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}\sqcup\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{0} & \text{if }p'\neq0\\
\mathrm{Spec}(\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle x^{2},xy\rangle) & \text{if }p=0.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cuspidal Cubic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash f$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f=y^{2}-x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega_{S\slash\Bbbk}=\frac{S\mathrm{d}x\oplus S\mathrm{d}y}{-3x^{2}\mathrm{d}x+2y\mathrm{d}y}.
\]

\end_inset

In order to better understand what kind of object 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{S\slash\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 is, we digress a bit and explain how one should think 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in terms of geometry.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,S$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=(a,b)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}=a^{3}$
\end_inset

, we have a maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{p}}=\langle x-a,y-b\rangle$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (or alternatively we can consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{p}}$
\end_inset

 as a closed point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

) and we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk_{\boldsymbol{p}}:=S\slash\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{p}}\simeq\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 to be the corresponding residue field (which is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 but equipped with an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module action coming from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, then these are all of the maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, however if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is not algebraically closed, then there will be more maximal ideals than
 just this.
 For instance, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the set of all such closed points forms the curve below:
\begin_inset Branch tikzcd
inverted 0
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines=none,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmax=2.5, xmin=-2.5, ymax=2.5, ymin=-2.5, ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=-4:4,samples=100,color=black,thick] ({x^2 }, {x^3 });
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=left:$(0
\backslash
text{,} 0)$] (y) at (axis cs:0,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=right:$(1
\backslash
text{,} 1)$] (y) at (axis cs:1,1) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

However 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 contains more closed points than just this (alternatively 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 contains more maximal ideals than just this).
 Indeed, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=(a,b)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}=a^{3}$
\end_inset

, one gets an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\boldsymbol{p}}\colon S\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\mapsto b$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\boldsymbol{p}}$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset


\series bold
-valued point 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (or a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-valued point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
 For any such 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-valued point, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{p}}:=\ker e_{\boldsymbol{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then all maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are obtained this way (i.e.
 as the kernel of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-valued point).
 Furthermore, for two such points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p},\boldsymbol{p}'$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{p}}=\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{p}'}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\sigma\boldsymbol{p}}=e_{\boldsymbol{p}'}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{C}\slash\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\boldsymbol{p}=\sigma(a,b)=(\sigma a,\sigma b)$
\end_inset

.
 This holds more generally in the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk\neq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, choose an algebraic closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have natural bijections:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \text{maximal ideals of }S\right\} \simeq\{\text{closed points of }X\}\simeq\{\overline{\Bbbk}\text{-valued points of }X\}\slash\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}\sim\boldsymbol{p}'$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=\sigma\boldsymbol{p}'$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mathrm{Gal}(\overline{\Bbbk}\slash\Bbbk)$
\end_inset

.
 With this in mind, recall that for each closed point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(\Omega_{S\slash\Bbbk},\Bbbk_{\boldsymbol{p}})=\{\text{point derivations \ensuremath{\partial}}\colon S\to\Bbbk_{\boldsymbol{p}}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus we can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(\Omega_{S\slash\Bbbk},\Bbbk_{\boldsymbol{p}})$
\end_inset

 as the set of all tangent vectors at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the point derivations at the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}=(0,0)$
\end_inset

 correspond to all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=(v_{x},v_{y})\in\Bbbk^{2}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}\widetilde{\partial}_{x}|_{\boldsymbol{0}}+v_{y}\widetilde{\partial}_{y}|_{\boldsymbol{0}}$
\end_inset

 vanishes on 
\begin_inset Formula $2y\mathrm{d}y-3x^{2}\mathrm{d}x$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the point derivations at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=(1,1)$
\end_inset

 correspond to all vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}\in\Bbbk^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $-3v_{x}+2v_{y}=0$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(v_{x}\widetilde{\partial}_{x}|_{\boldsymbol{p}}+v_{y}\widetilde{\partial}_{y}|_{\boldsymbol{p}})(2y\mathrm{d}y-3x^{2}\mathrm{d}x)=-3v_{x}+2v_{y}=0.
\]

\end_inset

For instance, the point derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/3)\widetilde{\partial}_{x}|_{\boldsymbol{p}}+(1/2)\widetilde{\partial}_{y}|_{\boldsymbol{p}}$
\end_inset

 can be visualized on the curve as the tangent vector centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

 as below:
\begin_inset Branch tikzcd
inverted 0
status collapsed

