\begin_layout Section
Parametrizing Field Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field and fix an algebraic closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\Bbbk[x_{1},\dots,x_{n},y_{1},\dots,y_{n}]\slash\langle y_{1}-e_{1},\dots,y_{n}-e_{n}\rangle=\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}]\slash\langle\boldsymbol{y}-\boldsymbol{e}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th elementary symmetric polynomial
\series bold
:
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }k=0\\
\sum_{1\leq j_{1}<\cdots<j_{i}\leq n}x_{j_{1}}\cdots x_{j_{i}} & \text{if }k\leq n\\
0 & \text{if }k>n
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

We view 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]$
\end_inset

-algebra via the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]\to A$
\end_inset

 which sends 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 ot 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we view 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra via the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

 which sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]\to\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

 which sends 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Geometrically speaking, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the morphism of affine 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $e\colon\mathbb{A}^{n}\to\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}:=\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{n}$
\end_inset

, which sends a 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

-valued point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}=(r_{1},\dots,r_{n})\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{\Bbbk})$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

-valued point 
\begin_inset Formula $e(\boldsymbol{r})=(e_{1}(\boldsymbol{r}),\dots,e_{n}(\boldsymbol{r}))\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{\Bbbk})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}]\twoheadrightarrow A\to\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma_{e}\colon\mathbb{A}^{n}\xrightarrow{\simeq}X:=\mathrm{Spec}\,A\subset\mathrm{Spec}\,(\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}])\simeq\mathbb{A}^{n}\times_{\Bbbk}\mathbb{A}^{n},
\]

\end_inset

which is given on 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

-valued points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{\Bbbk})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\mapsto(\boldsymbol{r},e(\boldsymbol{r}))$
\end_inset

.
 Finally the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]\to A$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 which is given on 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

-valued points 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{c})\in X(\overline{\Bbbk})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{c})\mapsto\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that since the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 are algebraically independent, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebras of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]$
\end_inset

 onto its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{e}]=\Bbbk[e_{1},\dots,e_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]\to\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{e}]\subseteq\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}=(c_{1},\dots,c_{n})\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{\Bbbk})$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{e}_{\boldsymbol{c}}\colon\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]\twoheadrightarrow\Bbbk(\boldsymbol{c})\subseteq\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{e}_{\boldsymbol{c}}(y_{i})=c_{i}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{c}}=\ker\mathrm{e}_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 be the monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk(\boldsymbol{c})[t]$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}:=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}c_{i}t^{n-i}=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}e_{i}(\boldsymbol{r})t^{n-i}=\prod_{i=1}^{n}(t-r_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=r_{\boldsymbol{c},i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 (for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 we arbitrarily fix an ordering 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{\boldsymbol{c}}=\boldsymbol{r}=r_{1},\dots,r_{n}$
\end_inset

 of the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

, for instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, then we can order them likeso: given 
\begin_inset Formula $z=re^{i\theta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z'=r'e^{i\theta'}$
\end_inset

 are two nonzero complex numbers expressed in polarized form with 
\begin_inset Formula $r,r'>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\theta'\in[0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $z\geq z'$
\end_inset

 if either 
\begin_inset Formula $r>r'$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|r|=|r'|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>\theta'$
\end_inset

, and we extend this by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $z\geq0$
\end_inset

).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\boldsymbol{c}}=\mathrm{Gal}(\Bbbk(\boldsymbol{r}_{\boldsymbol{c}},\boldsymbol{c})\slash\Bbbk(\boldsymbol{c}))$
\end_inset

 and finally let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\boldsymbol{c}}=A\otimes_{\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]}\Bbbk(\boldsymbol{c})\simeq\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]\slash\langle\boldsymbol{c}-\boldsymbol{e}\rangle
\]

\end_inset

be the fiber of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

