label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With the notation as above, we have a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{\boldsymbol{c}}\backslash S_{n}\cong|\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{\boldsymbol{c}}|.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 is finite as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon B_{\boldsymbol{c}}\to\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by what it does to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{y}}$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{y}}\mapsto\boldsymbol{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\gamma}=(\gamma_{1},\dots,\gamma_{n})\in\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y},t]$
\end_inset

 we have the polynomial identity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{i=1}^{n}(t-y_{i})=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}e_{i}t^{n-i}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\overline{\boldsymbol{e}}}}=\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{i=1}^{n}(t-\gamma_{i})=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}c_{i}t^{n-i}=\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}},
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\rho\boldsymbol{r}=(r_{\rho(1)},\dots,r_{\rho(n)})$
\end_inset

 for some permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\overline{\boldsymbol{y}})=\boldsymbol{r}$
\end_inset

.
 Then every 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\boldsymbol{c}}\to\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 must have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\rho$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}_{1},\dots,\overline{y}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, there are only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\boldsymbol{c}}\to\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

, and each of them surjects onto 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 The maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 are precisely of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker(\varphi\rho)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker(\varphi\rho)=\ker(\varphi\rho')$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho'=\sigma\rho$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mathrm{Gal}(L_{\boldsymbol{c}}\slash\Bbbk)$
\end_inset

 is viewed as the permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}_{1},\dots,\overline{y}_{n}$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to how 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 permutes the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\dots,r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the fiber over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 is bijection with the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Gal}(L(\boldsymbol{c})\slash\Bbbk)\backslash S_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we projectivize everything.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{A}=A[z]$
\end_inset

 and let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{B}=A[\boldsymbol{y},z]\slash\langle x_{1}-e_{1},zx_{2}-e_{2},\dots,z^{n-1}x_{n}-e_{n}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})\colon\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n}\to\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be the morphism given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}(\boldsymbol{r})=e_{i}(\boldsymbol{r})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}=(r_{1},\dots,r_{n})\in\overline{\Bbbk}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}=(c_{1},\dots,c_{n})\in\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 be the monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}[t]$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}c_{i}t^{n-i}=\prod_{i=1}^{n}(t-r_{i})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=r_{i,\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 (for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 we arbitrarily fix an ordering 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{\boldsymbol{c}}=\boldsymbol{r}=(r_{1},\dots,r_{n})$
\end_inset

 of the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

).
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also let 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\boldsymbol{c})=\Bbbk(\boldsymbol{r})$
\end_inset

 be the splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}'=(c_{1}',\dots,c_{n}')\in\Bbbk^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}\neq\boldsymbol{c}'$
\end_inset

, then we may have 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\boldsymbol{c})=L(\boldsymbol{c}')$
\end_inset

 even though 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}\neq\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{\boldsymbol{c}}\neq\boldsymbol{r}_{\boldsymbol{c}'}$
\end_inset

.
 there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\in$
\end_inset

 map is onto.
 Indeed, note that in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x},t]$
\end_inset

 we have the polynomial identity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{i=1}^{n}(t-x_{i})=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}e_{i}t^{n-i}.
\]

\end_inset

Now given any closed point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}=(c_{1},\dots,c_{n})\in\overline{\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

, form the monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}[t]$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}c_{i}t^{n-i}.
\]

\end_inset

Then Then in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Bbbk}[$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\boldsymbol{c}}=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}c_{i}t^{n-i}=\prod_{i=1}^{n}(t-r_{i})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{i=1}^{n}(t-y_{i})=t^{n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}e_{i}t^{n-i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Algebraically speaking, the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\overline{\Bbbk}[\boldsymbol{x}]\to\overline{\Bbbk}[\boldsymbol{y}]$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{i})=e_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi=0$
\end_inset

 since the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 are algebraically independent, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{f(\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n})}=\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

.
 is a we may also identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 with the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, We factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n}\xrightarrow{\Gamma_{f}}\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n}\times\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n}\xrightarrow{\pi_{2}}\mathbb{A}_{\overline{\Bbbk}}^{n},
\]

\end_inset

where the first morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{f}$
\end_inset

, called the graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{r},f(\boldsymbol{r}))$
\end_inset

 and where the second morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the projection map onto the second coordiante, that is, it takes 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{c})$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Algebraically speaking, the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{f}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]\otimes_{\Bbbk}\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{y}]=\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}]\xrightarrow{}\Bbbk[\boldsymbol{x}]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

